Caption:
Barleys include species from the genus Hordeum. These spike-like grasses have their small spikelets arranged together in triplets, held together by a short stalk. Each triplet is positioned on top of another, creating a spike. When the spikelets are mature, the triplets readily break off. Hordeum species are annuals, or occasionally longer-lived perennials.

Each spikelet within a triplet has only 1 floret, which is rounded and hard. The glumes are equal in length, very narrow and often long-awned. The lemmas have long- very long awns arising from the tips.

This is Hordeum murinum or Wall Barley. This common species is a stout spike comprised of stacked triplets of spikelets. The glumes are narrow and awned. The lemmas have very long awns, around four times longer than the rest of the lemma. An annual species found on waste-ground and road-sides.

Caption:
Grasses from the genus Phleum, include Cat’s-tails and Timothy. The inflorescence is a panicle which is so contracted it resembles a dense, cylindrical spike. The leaves are flat. Species are usually perennials, growing in tufts.

Spikelets contain 1 floret. Glumes are equal in length and have awns, giving the spikelet a horned appearance. The lemmas are always awn-less.

This is Phleum pratense or Timothy. A common species, up to 150cm tall, with a cylindrical spike, around 15cm long. The leaves are flat and ligules blunt. A tufted perennial growing in grassland and waste-land.
